'''Song Bum-keun''' ({{langx|ko|송범근}}; born 15 October 1997) is a South Korean professional footballer who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[K League 1]] club [[Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors]] and the [[South Korea national football team|South Korea national team]].

==Club career==

===Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors===
On 20 February 2018, Song made his professional debut in [[2018 AFC Champions League group stage|2018 AFC Champions League]] against [[Kitchee SC]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-12-20 |title=Song Bum-keun joins J1 League club Shonan Bellmare |url=https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/2022/12/20/sports/football/Korea-K-League-Song-Bumkeun/20221220154543242.html |access-date=2023-08-30 |website=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]] |language=en}}</ref>

===Shonan Bellmare===
On 18 December 2022, Song officially joined Japanese side [[Shonan Bellmare]] on a permanent transfer.<ref>{{cite web |date=18 December 2022 |title=全北現代 ソン ボムグン選手 完全移籍加入のお知らせ |url=https://www.bellmare.co.jp/300416 |access-date=18 December 2022 |website=Shonan Bellamare |language=ja}}</ref>

=== Return to Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors ===
On 2 January 2025, Song returned to Jeonbuk, joining the club as a free agent.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-01-02 |title=Goalkeeper Song Bum-keun returns to Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors |url=https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/2025-01-02/sports/football/Goalkeeper-Song-Bumkeun-returns-to-Jeonbuk-Hyundai-Motors/2213786 |access-date=2026-03-03 |website=Korea JoongAng Daily |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Song has represented South Korea at all groups from under-18 to senior level. He was the team's first choice goalkeeper for the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] and the [[2020 AFC U-23 Championship]], winning the latter and being named Best Goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-afc.com/en/national/afc_u23_asian_cup/news/korea_republics_song_named_best_goalkeeper_thailands_wonggorn_wins_top_scorer_award.html|title=Korea Republic's Song named Best Goalkeeper, Thailand's Wonggorn wins Top Scorer Award|date=27 January 2020|access-date=16 May 2026|website=AFC}}</ref> In 2021, he represented South Korea at the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics|Tokyo Olympic Games]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/2021/07/31/sports/olympics/Team-Korea-Mexico-Tokyo-Olympics/20210731225300467.html|title=Korea crashes out of Olympic football contest with 6-3 loss to Mexico|date=31 July 2021|access-date=16 May 2026|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> 

On 24 July 2022, Song made his debut for the senior [[Korea Republic national football team]], keeping a clean sheet in a 3–0 win over [[Hong Kong national football team|Hong Kong]] in the [[2022 EAFF E-1 Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sbs.co.kr/news/endPage.do?news_id=N1007011621|title=전북 골키퍼 송범근, J리그 쇼난 벨마레로 이적|date=18 December 2022|access-date=16 May 2026|language=Korean|website=SBS}}</ref> Later that year, he was a member of the Korean squad at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], serving as back-up to [[Kim Seung-gyu]] and [[Jo Hyeon-woo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3739142/2022/11/08/south-korea-2022-world-cup-squad-news/|title=South Korea World Cup squad list for round of 16 fixture against Brazil|date=9 November 2022|access-date=16 May 2026|website=The Athletic}}</ref>

On 16 May 2026, Song was named in South Korea's squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cwy29rxjg47o|title=South Korea captain Son picked for fourth World Cup|date=16 May 2026|access-date=16 May 2026|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

